    <h1 id="overview">Below the NOI line adjustments</h1>
    <h2>How to calculate the Net Realizable Reversion Value</h2>
    <br>
    <p>
      After calculating the Initial Reversionary Value, several additional
      adjustments are necessary to arrive at the Net Realizable Reversionary
      Value. These 'below the line' adjustments account for factors beyond the
      property's operational performance, including market conditions,
      transaction-related expenses, and seller-specific costs. These adjustments
      are one-to-one adjustments in the valuation and refine the Initial
      Reversionary Value to the actual amount a seller can expect to receive
      from the property sale.
    </p>
    <hr class="mt-2 mb-6 border-gray-300">
    <h3>Sale Price Adjustments</h3>
    <p>
      Sale Price Adjustments are adjustments made to account for market
      conditions, property specifics not captured in the NOI<sub>Adj</sub> or
      adjustments expected in negotiations. Examples of items that may be
      included in Sale Price Adjustments include: upcoming Capital Expenses,
      deferred maintenance, expected functional obsolescence or excess land
      value.
    </p>
    <p>
      Sale Price Adjustments are added or subtracted from the Initial
      Reversionary Value to arrive at the Adjusted Reversionary Value–the
      theoretical gross price that a buyer and seller would agree upon in a
      frictionless market (ie. no transaction costs).
    </p>
    <p>
      ReturnSuite offers two options for Sale Price Adjustments:
    </p>
    <ol class="list-decimal pl-8 text-gray-800 text-base pb-2 leading-8">
      <li><b>Amount</b> - a fixed dollar amount, or</li>
      <li><b>Percentage of Initial Reversionary Value</b> - a variable amount which is a percentage of the Initial Reversionary Value</li>
    </ol>
    <hr class="mt-2 mb-6 border-gray-300">
    <h4>Example</h4>
    <p>
      Continuing with our example, let’s say we expect the following two Sale Price Adjustments:
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-8 text-gray-800 text-base pb-4 leading-8">
      <li>
        A major HVAC system upgrade which will be needed shortly due to changing
        energy efficiency regulations that are expected to come into effect
        shortly after the expected closing date. Based on the current levels of
        inflation and current construction costs, the upgrade is expected to
        cost $130,000 at the End Date of the Analysis Period.
      </li>
      <li>
        Undeveloped land adjacent to the property but not earning any income.
        The landlord has no plans to develop the land, but it does allow for
        the development of additional leasable space. Given current site
        coverage ratios, the land is estimated to have a market value of 8.0%
        of the Initial Reversionary Value.
      </li>
    </ul>
