            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <figcaption>Adjusted Reversionary Value</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Since the HVAC system upgrade is a Capital Expense, it won’t show up in
      the NOI, but the investment will be required to maintain the cash flow
      generating ability of the property. It therefore makes sense for a
      potential buyer to demand a downward Sale Price Adjustment of $130,000.
    </p>
    <p>
      The undeveloped land adds value to the property, so the landlord can
      reasonably expect to demand a higher purchase price for the property.
      The land is expected to add $461,125 (8.5% x $5,425,000) to the Initial
      Reversionary Value.
    </p>
    <hr class="mt-2 mb-6 border-gray-300">
    <h3>Transaction Costs</h3>
    <p>
      Transaction Costs include all the direct costs associated with completing
      the sale, such as brokerage fees, legal expenses, and marketing costs.
    </p>
    <p>
      Transaction Costs are subtracted from the Adjusted Reversionary Value to
      arrive at the Net Reversionary Value–the net sale price of the property
      or the true economic value of a property after all standard market
      transaction costs are accounted for.
    </p>
    <p>
      Note: Transaction Costs should include any buyer costs if they would be
      incurred by all potential buyers of the property since they impact the
      effective price a buyer is willing to pay to achieve their target return.
      By factoring in <a href="#">both buyer and seller transaction costs</a>,
      we arrive at a more accurate representation of the property's true
      economic value in the market.
    </p>
    <p>
      ReturnSuite offers three options for Transaction Costs:
    </p>
    <ol class="list-decimal pl-8 text-gray-800 text-base pb-2 leading-8">
